ller's association. Additionally, I'm verifying the access permissions based on role, with the understanding that clients can only view their tickets.\n\n\n**Mapping Payload and Properties**\n\nI'm now carefully mapping the payload fields to our internal properties. I've realized we need to support both `title` and `subject`, mapping them to `subject`. Similarly, I'll support both `description` and `desc`. I'm verifying the input keys: `title`, `description`, `category`, `priority`, `status`, `client_id`, `project_id`, `assigned_to`, and `created_by`. I'm making sure that the existing `ApiSupportTicket` properties support the expected input fields.\n\n\n**Defining Input Field Mappings**\n\nI'm now implementing the detailed input field mappings. For `priority`, I'll accept string values like \"high,\" \"medium,\" \"low,\" or \"critical\" and map them to the proper values. The same applies for \"OPEN,\" \"INVESTIGATING,\" etc. I'll automatically resolve `client_name` from `client_id` using `getClientNameFromId()`. For `project_id` and `assigned_to`, I'll support and store both relevant property names. Now, I'll incorporate the `created_by` field, too.\n\n\n**Enforcing Client ID Restrictions**\n\nI'm now implementing client ID validation for ticket creation. If a user isn't an admin or support agent, I'll restrict the `client_id` they can specify to their own. Admins and support roles can create tickets for any client. I'll use the caller's ID if the client isn't specified, or resolve it to \"client-unknown.\" I'm also confirming the proper filter inclusion.\n\n\n**Implementing GET Filters**\n\nI'm now implementing the GET filters in the support list endpoint. I've examined the existing `GET` list endpoint and will add filters for `project_id`, `assigned_to`. I'm also now implementing case-insensitive filtering. I'll normalize `priorityFilter` input and handle multiple client IDs with an array filter. I'm focusing on ensuring these filter functions perform reliably.\n\